  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n- Mandates reporting of certain financial transactions\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988\n- Expanded money laundering laws to include more financial crimes\n- Enhanced penalties for money laundering related to drug trafficking\n\n4. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Strengthened anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and enforcement mechanisms\n- Expanded the definition of money laundering\n\n5. The Bank Secrecy Act Anti-Money Laundering Act (AMLA) of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing anti-money laundering regulations\n- Established new beneficial ownership reporting requirements\n\nThese statutes collectively provide a comprehensive legal framework for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.",
